annotation.TEXT: I'm going to be honest: The only reason Bomber Man is annoying here is because his weakness is Spider Strings. Beyond that, he's kind of an unremarkable boss.

Taking even more inspiration from awful weapons: Hudson Bomb is just the Hyper Bomb from MM1, but with Bomberman styled explosions. Even though it has a higher ammo count than some of the other weapons, it's still just as useless as it was in the original.

Continuing with the "this weapon is like ____ but not as good" trope, Spider Strings is essentially an even worse version of Silver Tomahawk. Its arching paths are so unorthodox that it makes hitting anything with them to be almost luck-based at first. You can actually hold up or down to change the trajectory slightly, but even then, it's still awful to position correctly.

Sugoi Man (who is actually Jin Fu-Ha from Art of Fighting) is a bit trickier than Kung Fu Man, but not by too much. The only real difficulty comes from the odd trajectories of his spinning attacks, which can be annoying to jump over even without Mugen 1.0 causing a delay on your controls.

Aside from maybe Trillion Flare, Seikimatsu Bazooka is the only weapon in this game that's half-way decent. It has a good ammo count, and its projectiles home in on targets. The only problem is that the actual projectiles are way too slow, essentially only making it useful around point-blank range.

Kym Knuckle is basically the Power Adapter's uncharged shot from MM6, but as a standalone weapon. It has 28 shots, has short range, and is basically near-useless (even against things that are weak to it).

Time for the weapons...and I'm not going to lie: Every single weapon in this game is downright horrible. Even by boss rush-type standards, this is easily one of the worst weapon sets in any fan-game I've seen (even more-so than Mega Man Rocks or Super Mega Man 3).

Z Man (who seems to be based on Zetton from Ultraman) is hands down, the single, biggest, pain-in-the-ass boss in this entire game. His main tactics include teleporting right on top of you with little way to avoid it, and a gigantic flare attack that can kill you in 3 hits. If he's feeling indifferent, he'll also randomly jump and spew out 3 smaller shots as well.

Time to start with the basics: This game is essentially a gigantic parody of sorts, taking the form of a boss rush from start to finish (somewhat akin to Mega Man's Christmas Carol). Mega Man himself controls like he did in MM2 (no surprise there), but at the same time, his movements definitely feel a bit off (I blame this mostly on Mugen 1.0's engine, which I'll go into detail on later).

Ryuei Shield creates two spinning barriers around Mega Man, both of which can cancel out projectiles (that is, if they don't go through the openings of it). Aside from not being a very good shield, it has a pitifully low ammo count that makes it one of the most annoying weakness affiliations in the game.
Just to note, he actually does have one other attack (where he throws planks of wood from his original intro at you), though he didn't get the chance to use it here.

I may as well get this out of the way now: Mugen 1.0 is terrible when it comes to pressing multiple buttons at the same time. For a game like this, it's virtually impossible to do something like charge a weapon, jump, and hold a direction without Mugen 1.0 locking up one of the inputs. This is the reason why Mega Man outright doesn't jump at times in this game.

As if that intro was any indication, we're taking a look at a unique specimen today. This is "Rockman Infinity" by Ukege, a game made in the Mugen 1.0 engine, of all things. Then again, this isn't exactly the first time this sort of thing has been done. A classic full game for the original engine was released all the way back in 2005, but it was nowhere near as extensive as this.
Even though I somehow managed to get a perfect on this guy, trust me: It's nowhere near as easy as it looks.

Howard Man (Rock Howard from Garou: Mark of the Wolves) is one of the most irritating bosses in the game. Aside from being incredibly fast, his "Rising Tackle" is performed randomly during his rush moves, meaning you'll most likely get hit by it as you try to jump over him.

Kym Man (who appears to be based on Sagara Sanosuke from Rurouni Kenshin) is thankfully much easier than Howard Man. The only difficulty in this fight comes from his charging attack, which even with its start-up, is incredibly fast and damaging.

Trillion Flare is kind of like a cross between Atomic Fire and Magma Bazooka. Uncharged fires a single shot, mid-charge fires a three-way spread, and full-charge releases a gigantic shot. While the premise is neat, its ammo feels way too limited to make proper use of it at times. Also, Mugen 1.0's input delays can prevent you from charging and jumping to the left or right at the same time.

Reppu Wave fires in a small arc above you when you first launch it, and then crawls along the ground until it hits something. If Mega Man performed the original motion for it, along with making it bigger/stronger, that would actually be kind of cool. Instead though, it's basically a weaker version of Search Snake.

Zagi Man (basically a robo-version of Jagi from Fist of the North Star) is actually quite easy to deal with. The problem, once again, is within his weakness. Trillion Flare's mechanics combined with Mugen 1.0's control delays will give you little chance to avoid his attacks.
Also, don't jump next to him when he does that move. Those text boxes can actually hurt you if touch them.

Spider Man (or "Spider Ma" as the game likes to call him) isn't quite as annoying as Howard Man, but he's still a bit of a pain to deal with. His projectiles have both a somewhat strange path and a long hit-stun time. He's essentially one of the more random opponents in terms of overall movements.
Anyways, here's Kung Fu Man. He's the easiest boss in the game, and is probably the best of the 8 to start with. He essentially serves as a tutorial opponent for getting used to your movements.

Starting off, we have the Kung-Fu Board. It shoots out a plank of wood with rapid-fire capabilities. It would be a decent buster replacement, but in a setting like this, it's downright useless against anything that doesn't have a weakness affiliation to it.
